    <!-- CHAPTER 01 — THE ORDINANCE                            -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <section class="chapter">
      <div class="chapter-inner" data-reveal>
        <div class="chapter-header">
          <span class="chapter-num">01</span>
          <div style="flex:1; min-width: 280px;">
            <div class="chapter-eyebrow">The ordinance</div>
            <h2 class="chapter-title">
              Denver Revised Municipal Code § 38-130
            </h2>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="chapter-lede">
          Title II, Chapter 38, Article IV, Division 2 — <em
            >Weapons and Missiles</em
          >. Passed by Denver City Council on a 9–4 vote in October 1989, signed
          by Mayor Federico Peña, and effective on
          <em>14 November 1989</em>. The ordinance has been amended once
          materially since: in <em>January 2018</em> to add bump stocks. It has never
          been repealed.
        </p>

        <div class="fact-grid">
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Enacting law</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              Council Ord. No. 669
              <small>October 1989</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Effective</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              14 November 1989
              <small>37 years in force</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Council vote</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              9 — 4
              <small>Yea: includes Cathy Reynolds</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Signed by</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              Mayor Federico Peña
              <small>41st Mayor of Denver, 1983–1991</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Recommended by</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              Chief Aristedes Zavaras
              <small>Denver Police Department</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Last material amendment</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              22 January 2018
              <small>Bump-stock prohibition added</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Penalty range</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              $100–$999 fine · up to 180 days
              <small>Bump stock: 10-day mandatory minimum</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Enforcement venue</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              Denver Co. Municipal Court
              <small>Not state-classified misdemeanor</small>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="sub">The legislative finding (the city's own words)</h3>

        <div class="statute" aria-label="DRMC § 38-130 legislative finding">
          <div class="statute-line">
            <div class="statute-num">a)</div>
            <div class="statute-text">
              The City Council finds that <b
                >"the use of assault weapons poses a threat to the health,
                safety, and security of all citizens of the City and County of
                Denver"</b
              > and that such weapons <b
                >"are capable both of a rapid rate of fire as well as of a
                capacity to fire an inordinately large number of rounds without
                reloading and are designed primarily for military or
                antipersonnel use."</b
              >
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="body">
          Two pieces of legislative bait-and-switch are baked into that
          paragraph. First, <strong>"rapid rate of fire"</strong> — a phrase that
          does no work unless you intend it to mean <em>any</em> rifle that cycles
          a round per trigger pull, which describes more than half of rifles sold
          in America. Second, <strong
            >"designed primarily for military or antipersonnel use"</strong
          > — a finding the city makes for itself, by ordinance, without testimony
          from a single firearms designer or military procurement officer in the legislative
          record. The Stoner platform was drawn up for the civilian market in 1958.
          Eugene Stoner did not work for the Pentagon. He worked for ArmaLite. Denver
          wrote what suited Denver.
        </p>

        <h3 class="sub">What § 38-130 actually bans</h3>

        <div class="two-col">
          <div class="col-card crimson">
            <div class="col-head">
              <div class="col-head-num">×</div>
              <div class="col-head-text">Prohibited</div>
            </div>
            <ul class="col-list">
              <li>
                <strong>Semiautomatic centerfire rifle</strong> with a detachable
                magazine that holds <em>more than 15 rounds</em>.
                <small>Catches every factory AR-15 and AK-pattern rifle.</small>
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Semiautomatic pistol</strong> with a detachable magazine that
                holds <em>more than 15 rounds</em>.
                <small>
                  Glock 17, Glock 19 with extended mag, full-size M&amp;P, CZ-75
                  — implicated.
                </small>
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Semiautomatic shotgun</strong> with a folding stock
                <em>and/or</em> a magazine over <em>6 rounds</em>.
                <small>Saiga 12, KSG, Mossberg 590M, Vepr-12.</small>
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Any firearm modified</strong> to operate as one of the above,
                plus parts intended to convert a firearm into an "assault weapon."
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Bump stocks</strong> — added 22 January 2018, before the federal
                rule took effect.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong
                  >Carry, store, keep, manufacture, sell, or possess</strong
                >
                — the verbs cover almost every conceivable touch of a covered firearm
                inside city limits.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <div class="col-card gold">
            <div class="col-head">
              <div class="col-head-num">✓</div>
              <div class="col-head-text">Exempted</div>
            </div>
            <ul class="col-list">
              <li>
                <strong>Law enforcement</strong> on duty — federal, state, or local.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Active military</strong> in the lawful course of service.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Licensed security guards</strong> within the scope of employment.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Movie and theatrical props</strong> — the Hollywood exception.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Nonresidents transporting</strong> firearms through the city
                without "undue delay."
                <small>
                  No definition of "undue." Practical effect: drive faster.
                </small>
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Pre-1989 grandfather</strong> — owners who lawfully possessed
                the firearm before 14 November 1989
                <em>and</em> registered it with DPD under the permitting system. Permits
                are confidential by ordinance.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Excluded categories:</strong> bolt-action, lever-action, slide-action,
                single-shot or multiple-barrel firearms; pre-1954 semiautos; rimfire
                tube-magazine firearms.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="body">
          The grandfather clause is the part nobody talks about. It exists. It
          is on the books. But the registration window closed essentially the
          day the ordinance took effect, and the permit registry is confidential
          under municipal code, which means even <em>asking</em>
          how many grandfathered owners exist runs into a privacy wall the city itself
          built. The practical effect is a population frozen on 14 November 1989 with
          no path to add to it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- CHAPTER 02 — ARTICLE XX                               -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <section class="chapter alt">
      <div class="chapter-inner" data-reveal>
        <div class="chapter-header">
          <span class="chapter-num">02</span>
          <div style="flex:1; min-width: 280px;">
            <div class="chapter-eyebrow">The shield</div>
            <h2 class="chapter-title">
              Article XX &amp; the Home-Rule Carve-Out
            </h2>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="chapter-lede">
          Every conversation about Denver's gun laws collapses into one
          question: <em
            >how did this survive 18 years of statewide preemption?</em
          >
          The answer is one provision of the Colorado Constitution, ratified in 1902,
          that nobody outside the state bar quotes correctly.
        </p>

        <div class="const-card">
          <div class="const-eyebrow">
            Colo. Const. Art. XX § 6 — adopted 1902
          </div>
          <p class="const-text">
            "Such charter and the ordinances made pursuant thereto in such
            matters shall <strong style="color: var(--gold)"
              >supersede within the territorial limits</strong
            > of said city or town any law of the state in conflict therewith. <em
              >Such charter and the ordinances made pursuant thereto shall
              extend to all its local and municipal matters.</em
            >"
          </p>
          <div class="const-cite">
            Verbatim from the Colorado Constitution · home-rule grant · Denver
            designated home-rule city by the same article.
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="body">
          The Colorado Supreme Court has carved firearms regulation into three
          buckets. <strong>Local concern</strong> — home-rule city wins.
          <strong>State concern</strong> — state wins. <strong
            >Mixed concern</strong
          > — both can legislate so long as they do not directly conflict. The court
          ruled in <em>Robertson</em> that Denver's assault-weapon ordinance fell
          into the <strong>mixed</strong>
          category. The state had not preempted it in 1989, so it stood. When the
          legislature finally tried to preempt in 2003 — codified at C.R.S. § 29-11.7-103
          — Denver sued. Denver won. The 1989 ordinance continued in force.
        </p>

        <p class="body">
          From <strong>2003 to 2021</strong>, no other Colorado city could enact
          what Denver had. Boulder tried in 2018 and got struck down by the
          Boulder County District Court in <em>March 2021</em> — ten days before the
          King Soopers shooting, in which a man bought a Ruger AR-556 pistol six days
          before murdering ten people in a grocery store. The
          <em>same week</em> a state court invalidated Boulder's ordinance, someone
          who could not have legally bought that pistol the prior week murdered ten
          people with it. The legislature took the hint. SB21-256 dropped within sixty
          days.
        </p>

        <h3 class="sub">The 2003 carve-out, in plain English</h3>

        <p class="body">
          <strong>What state law said:</strong> A local government "shall not enact
          an ordinance, regulation, or other law that prohibits the sale, purchase,
          or possession of a firearm that a person may lawfully sell, purchase, or
          possess under state or federal law." That is a statewide preemption clause,
          full stop. <strong>What the Denver carve-out said:</strong> Article XX is
          in the <em>constitution</em>, and a statute can't override the
          constitution. Denver's pre-existing ordinance was protected by the
          home-rule grant, not by any dispensation from the legislature. The
          Denver District Court agreed. The Colorado Supreme Court left that
          result undisturbed. The ordinance kept running.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- CHAPTER 03 — ROBERTSON                                -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <section class="chapter">
      <div class="chapter-inner" data-reveal>
        <div class="chapter-header">
          <span class="chapter-num">03</span>
          <div style="flex:1; min-width: 280px;">
            <div class="chapter-eyebrow">The 1994 ruling</div>
            <h2 class="chapter-title">
              Robertson v. City and County of Denver
            </h2>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="chapter-lede">
          Decided 2 May 1994. Cited as <em>874 P.2d 325 (Colo. 1994)</em>.
          Opinion by Chief Justice Luis D. Rovira. The case Denver has waved at
          every challenger for thirty-two years. Plaintiff David Kopel — yes,
          <em>that</em> Kopel — did not lose all of it. He took out the worst part.
          But the spine survived.
        </p>

        <div class="fact-grid">
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Citation</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              874 P.2d 325 (Colo. 1994)
              <small>Case 93SA91 · En banc</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Decided</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              2 May 1994
              <small>Opinion: Chief Justice Rovira</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Plaintiffs</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              Robertson · Deatherage · Hecht
              <small>and David Jewell d/b/a Scotties Guns &amp; Militaria</small
              >
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Plaintiffs' counsel (incl.)</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              David B. Kopel
              <small>Independence Institute</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Trial court below</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              Denver District Court
              <small>Held § 38-130 unconstitutional · reversed</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Holding</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              Ordinance largely upheld
              <small>One subsection struck for vagueness</small>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h3 class="sub">What the court actually held</h3>

        <p class="body">
          <strong>Affirmed:</strong> § 38-130(b)(1)(c) — the "assault pistol" subsection
          that defined banned pistols by their <em>design ancestry</em>
          (i.e., pistols "designed from" certain ancestor military firearms) —
          <strong>void for vagueness</strong>. The court reasoned that the
          provision required a person "to learn not only what guns their pistol
          was designed from, but also . . . the design history of the ancestor
          guns." That is, the ordinance asked a normal person to be a firearms
          historian to avoid criminal liability. It did not pass.
        </p>

        <p class="body">
          <strong>Reversed:</strong> the trial court's holding that § 38-130 as a
          whole was unconstitutional. The Colorado Supreme Court held the ordinance
          did <em>not</em> violate Article II § 13 (the state right-to-bear-arms clause),
          was <em>not</em> impermissibly overbroad, and was within the city's police
          power. <strong>Result:</strong> the feature-based prongs — magazine capacity,
          folding stock, semiauto shotgun — survived.
        </p>

        <p class="body">
          The opinion was decided <strong
            >fourteen years before
            <em>Heller</em></strong
          >, sixteen years before <em>McDonald</em>
          incorporated the Second Amendment against the states, and
          <strong>twenty-eight years before <em>Bruen</em></strong> demolished interest-balancing
          in favor of text-and-history. <em>Robertson</em>
          is doctrinally a fossil. It has not been overruled by a Colorado court because
          no Colorado court has had to decide whether the federal Second Amendment,
          applied through the Fourteenth, blows it apart. That is precisely the question
          the DOJ has now teed up.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- CHAPTER 04 — SB21-256 + COPYCATS                      -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <section class="chapter alt">
      <div class="chapter-inner" data-reveal>
        <div class="chapter-header">
          <span class="chapter-num">04</span>
          <div style="flex:1; min-width: 280px;">
            <div class="chapter-eyebrow">The dam breaks</div>
            <h2 class="chapter-title">SB21-256 and the Cities That Followed</h2>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="chapter-lede">
          <em>"Local Regulation of Firearms."</em> Senate Third Reading 19–15. House
          Third Reading 39–24. Signed by Governor Jared Polis on
          <em>19 June 2021</em>. Colorado became the first state in the country
          to broadly repeal firearm preemption. Five home-rule cities and one
          county tried to copy what Denver had been doing since 1989.
        </p>

        <div class="fact-grid">
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Bill</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              SB21-256 — Local Regulation of Firearms
              <small
                >Sponsors: Sens. Fenberg, Moreno · Reps. Daugherty, Hooton</small
              >
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Senate vote</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              19 — 15
              <small>Third reading · 18 May 2021</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">House vote</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              39 — 24
              <small>Third reading · 3 June 2021</small>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="fact">
            <div class="fact-label">Signed</div>
            <div class="fact-value">
              19 June 2021
              <small>Gov. Jared Polis · effective same day</small>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="body">
          The bill replaced C.R.S. § 29-11.7-103 with language that allowed
          local governments to enact firearm restrictions <em
            >more restrictive than</em
          > state law, but not less. It also empowered them to ban concealed carry
          on government property and college campuses. Polis signed it ten weeks after
          King Soopers. The political reaction was immediate.
        </p>

        <div class="cities">
          <div class="cities-head">The new copycats</div>
          <div class="cities-sub">
            Status as of May 2026 — federal litigation status indicated
          </div>
          <div class="cities-grid">
            <div class="city holding">
              <div class="city-name">Denver</div>
              <div class="city-status">In force · 1989</div>
              <div class="city-detail">
                The original. Survived Robertson, the 2003 preemption statute,
                and Bruen. Now the named target of the DOJ's federal lawsuit.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="city partial">
              <div class="city-name">Boulder</div>
              <div class="city-status">Partially enjoined</div>
              <div class="city-detail">
                Re-passed AW ban June 2022 after the 2018 version was struck.
                Sale/transfer prohibitions enjoined; possession provisions
                partially enforceable per Judge Wang's July 2025 order.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="city partial">
              <div class="city-name">Boulder County</div>
              <div class="city-status">Enjoined since Aug 2022</div>
              <div class="city-detail">
                Ordinance 2022-5 stayed by Judge Sweeney citing Bruen, eight
                weeks after enactment. Rapid-fire trigger activator portion
                still enforced.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="city partial">
              <div class="city-name">Louisville</div>
              <div class="city-status">In litigation</div>
              <div class="city-detail">
                Ord. 1820 (June 2022). Subject to the consolidated federal case
                that survived partial dismissal in 2025.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="city fallen">
              <div class="city-name">Superior</div>
              <div class="city-status">TRO June 2022</div>
              <div class="city-detail">
                Judge Moore issued a temporary restraining order eighteen days
                after Town Ordinance O-9 took effect. Never enforced.
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="city fallen">
              <div class="city-name">Lafayette · Edgewater</div>
              <div class="city-status">Scaled back</div>
              <div class="city-detail">
                Both cities advanced gun-control packages in August 2022.
                Edgewater dropped most of it; only the open-carry provision
                survived.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="body">
          Read the table closely. <strong
            >Every single copycat is in court.</strong
          >
          The two that drew TROs collapsed within months. The three that are still
          standing are doing so because federal judges are picking apart their ordinances
          piece by piece — sale here, possession there. Only Denver, the original,
          has been allowed to operate without a federal injunction. The DOJ is no
          longer willing to grant that exception.
        </p>

        <h3 class="sub">The statewide attempts that didn't make it</h3>

        <div class="two-col">
          <div class="col-card">
            <div class="col-head">
              <div class="col-head-num" style="color: var(--ink-mid)">↯</div>
              <div class="col-head-text">HB23-1230</div>
            </div>
            <ul class="col-list" style="--bullet:'·'">
              <li style="border-left:none">
                Statewide assault-weapon ban introduced 2023.
                <strong>Died in committee.</strong>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="col-card">
            <div class="col-head">
              <div class="col-head-num" style="color: var(--ink-mid)">↯</div>
              <div class="col-head-text">HB24-1292</div>
            </div>
            <ul class="col-list">
              <li style="border-left:none">
                Passed Colorado House <strong>35–27</strong>
                <em>(first time any AW ban cleared a Colorado chamber)</em>.
                Died in Senate. Civil penalty would have been $250K first
                violation, $500K each thereafter.
              </li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="body">
          Then came <strong>SB25-003</strong>. Signed by Gov. Polis on
          <em>10 April 2025</em>. The legislature finally found a workaround:
          ban manufacture, distribution, sale, transfer and purchase of covered
          semiauto rifles, shotguns and gas-operated pistols statewide
          <em>unless</em> the buyer obtained a Colorado Parks &amp; Wildlife "Firearms
          Safety Course Eligibility Card." Sale prohibition takes effect <strong
            >1 August 2026</strong
          >. It's not a ban. It's a permit. That distinction will matter when
          the federal courts read it next to the Denver ordinance.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

