    <!-- CHAPTER 05 — TIMELINE                                 -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <section class="chapter">
      <div class="chapter-inner" data-reveal>
        <div class="chapter-header">
          <span class="chapter-num">05</span>
          <div style="flex:1; min-width: 280px;">
            <div class="chapter-eyebrow">Chronology</div>
            <h2 class="chapter-title">
              A Hundred-and-Twenty-Four-Year Timeline
            </h2>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="chapter-lede">
          From the constitutional grant of home-rule authority to a federal
          complaint in the District of Colorado. Every load-bearing date from
          <em>1902 to today</em>.
        </p>

        <div class="timeline" role="list">
          <div class="tl-row major">
            <div class="tl-date">1902</div>
            <div class="tl-marker"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
              <div class="tl-title">Article XX ratified</div>
              <div class="tl-detail">
                Colorado constitutional amendment establishes Denver as a
                home-rule city. Grants charter and ordinances <strong
                  >"the power to supersede"</strong
                > conflicting state law within the territorial limits.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="tl-row">
            <div class="tl-date">Mar 1989</div>
            <div class="tl-marker"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
              <div class="tl-title">MAC-11 rampage in Littleton</div>
              <div class="tl-detail">
                The precipitating event for Denver's ordinance — a south-suburb
                shooting that gave the council political cover to act.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="tl-row major">
            <div class="tl-date">Oct 1989</div>
            <div class="tl-marker"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
              <div class="tl-title">
                Denver Council passes Ordinance 669, 9–4
              </div>
              <div class="tl-detail">
                Recommended by Chief Aristedes Zavaras. Mayor Federico Peña
                signs. Effective <em>14 November 1989</em>.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="tl-row">
            <div class="tl-date">1990</div>
            <div class="tl-marker"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
              <div class="tl-title">Robertson lawsuit filed</div>
              <div class="tl-detail">
                Lawrence Robertson, Sharon Deatherage, Jeffrey Hecht, and David
                Jewell d/b/a Scotties Guns and Militaria sue in Denver District
                Court for declaratory judgment.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="tl-row major">
            <div class="tl-date">2 May 1994</div>
            <div class="tl-marker"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
              <div class="tl-title">
                Robertson v. Denver decided · 874 P.2d 325
              </div>
              <div class="tl-detail">
                Colorado Supreme Court reverses trial court and largely
                <strong>upholds</strong> § 38-130. Strikes only § 38-130(b)(1)(c)
                — the "assault pistol" subsection — for vagueness.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="tl-row">
            <div class="tl-date">2002</div>
            <div class="tl-marker"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
              <div class="tl-title">
                Trinen v. Denver — open and vehicle carry
              </div>
              <div class="tl-detail">
                Colo. Court of Appeals upholds DRMC §§ 38-117 and 38-118 under
                Denver's home-rule authority.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="tl-row">
            <div class="tl-date">18 Mar 2003</div>
            <div class="tl-marker"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
              <div class="tl-title">
                Statewide preemption (C.R.S. § 29-11.7-103)
              </div>
              <div class="tl-detail">
                Colorado preempts local firearm regulation. Denver immediately
                sues. Denver wins on Article XX grounds. Denver's ordinance
                continues in force as the <em>only</em> Colorado AW ban for eighteen
                years.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="tl-row">
            <div class="tl-date">20 Mar 2013</div>
            <div class="tl-marker"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
              <div class="tl-title">HB13-1224 — statewide 15-round mag cap</div>
              <div class="tl-detail">
                Gov. Hickenlooper signs. Effective 1 July 2013. Sponsor: Sen.
                Rhonda Fields. Upheld 7–0 by Colorado Supreme Court in 2020.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="tl-row">
            <div class="tl-date">22 Jan 2018</div>
            <div class="tl-marker"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
              <div class="tl-title">Bump stocks added to § 38-130</div>
              <div class="tl-detail">
                Sponsored by Councilman Rafael Espinoza. Councilman Kevin
                Flynn's amendment to grandfather 16–20-round magazines kept in
                the home failed 6–6.
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="tl-row">
            <div class="tl-date">May 2018</div>
            <div class="tl-marker"></div>
            <div class="tl-body">
